  <body>
    <p align="left">
      <font face="Courier New, monospace">Hello &lt;manager&gt;, </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">It has come to
        the attention of the SOC that on the date of: XXX and time XXX
        the
        web application default.aspx on server: <a href="https://xxx/"
          class="moz-txt-link-freetext">https://xxx</a>
        belonging to the &lt;team&gt; was experiencing directory
        traversal
        and, LFI (Local File Inclusion) like activity. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">The traffic
        originated from one IP address noted here: &lt;ip address&gt;
        and hit
        the server 219 times. The first event was logged at: &lt;first
        seen&gt;
        and the last event was logged at &lt;last seen&gt;. The scan
        lasted
        for a total of 45 seconds. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">It is suggested
        that the SOC review the files located in that web directory and
        perform any or all of the following with permission of the
        application owner: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">LFI / RFI
            testing on POST and body requests. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">LFI / RFI
            testing on URL/URI requests</font></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">This will assure
        that the information being seen is either noise or, the
        beginning
        stages of something that may impact the security and data the
        SOC is
        attempting to protect. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">If testing is
        outside the scope of the SOC it is advised that the
        vulnerability
        management team be looped into the matter to scan and determine
        if
        the traffic seen is in fact benign or something the application
        owner(s) need to submit a fix for. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">In addition to
        which, it is noted that during the scans and threat hunt
        searches,
        the SOC did not notice any file access logs for the server in
        question nor the web application. It is suggested that the
        application and server owner turn on object-access fail /
        success for
        the web server to determine if there are any attempts to break
        out of
        the webroot and scan for files system wide. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">Sample logs and
        threat hunts along with photos have been attacked to the e-mail
        along
        with the IP address information, threat metrics and country
        information. Should you have any further questions please do let
        us
        know. </font>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><br>
      <br>
    </p>
    <p align="left"><font face="Courier New, monospace">Thank you, </font>
    </p>
